  <header><h1>Alan Bell</h1><h2>Graphic Designer and Printmaker</h2></header>
    <main>
    <img src="https://www.nlgja.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/AlanBELL.jpg" class="portrait" alt="a bust shot of a black man with glasses in front of a white background">
    <section><p>Alan Bell is a black gay magazine designer and publisher active from the 1970s—1990s. I think of him as a historical figure because of his impact both within the intersectional black queer community and on queer design and publishing</p></section>
    <section><h3>Early Life</h3><p>Born in California on March 14th, 1945, Bell grew up with fascinated with printing since early childhood after his father brought home a printing press to try and fix it. He even jokingly states that if his father had brought home a airplane, he would’ve been a pilot.</p></section>
    <section><h3>Move to NYC</h3><p>In 1969, he moved to New York to reconnect with friends. During this time, he was on probation for draft dodging during the Vietnam war, but his parole officer got his court order rearranged so he could stay in NY and work at Bellevue Hospital. During his stay, he started off his publishing career by printing for friends & acquaintances until it gradually grew into a volunteer (non-paid) printing business. </p></section>
    <section><h3>Gaysweek</h3><p>From there he printed Gaysweek (1977-1979), the first queer newspaper in New York. It was published on a weekly basis, ranged from 8-32 pages, and featured queer new and topics such as spots or cruising. After a cease and desist from Newsweek, stagnation, and Bell experiencing homelessness, Gaysweek ended its run in 1979 after 104 issues published.</p></section>
    <img src="http://pridemuseum.plus/Pride%20Museum%20Plus%20Items/LGBTQ%20Items/1987%20Gaysweek%20Magazine%20New%20York/Gaysweek%20New%2067%20September%201987.jpg" alt="a black, white, and orange newspaper cover titled Gaysweek">
    <section><h3>Return to LA and Blackjack</h3><p>Bell then moved back to LA where he became integrated with the black queer community and its members such as Jewel Williams and Phil Wilson. After witnessing the work of the Minority Aids Project, a non-profit organization meant to encourage and promote having safe sex to LGBT people during the AIDS crisis, he started Blackjack, an initiative to encourage black gay men to meet up and practice safe sex in a controlled environment. Blackjack would then become the first gay sex club for black gay men.</p></section>
    <section><h3>BLK magazine and Similar Publications</h3><p>Inspired by the flyers and application forms for Blackjack, he started his second major publication BLK Magazine, the first queer magazine made by and for black queer people published on a monthly basis.<br><br>The magazines frequently featured interviews with prominent black queer people such as RuPaul and Audre Lorde, and organizations such as The National Cotillion of Black Gays and Lesbians<br><br>As BLK Magazine was published on a monthly basis, some of Bell’s other works to help fund publishing include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Blackfire:</strong> a bimonthly erotica for black gay men.</li>
      <li><strong>Blacklace:</strong> a quarterly erotica for black gay women</li>
      <li><strong>Kuumba:</strong> a semiannual poetry & art journal with submissions from black gay people.</li>
    </ul>
    </section>
    <img src="https://thumbs.peoplesgdarchive.org/static/media-items/image/3565/upto-2880x2136/61ba255e/@2x/EO6hcRyWkAMUtBt.jpg?tgt=webp" alt="a magazine with a headshot of a black woman turning towards the camera">
    <section><h3>IDUG (2010—present)</h3><p>While Alan bell isn't actively designing, he's still active within the design space as the Managing Director for IDUG, or the InDesign User Group, in LA; IDUG is an organization that offers users resources, support, and events for Adobe InDesign.</p></section>
